This article is a proclamation made by President Barack Obama on December 10, 2012, declaring Human Rights Day and Human Rights Week. The proclamation commemorates the adoption of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which recognized the inherent dignity and inalienable rights of all people. The United States, as a nation built on the principles of freedom and fairness, has worked to promote these rights both domestically and abroad. The proclamation calls for the fortification of civil rights in America and the commitment to a world free from extrajudicial killing, torture, oppression, and discrimination. President Obama encourages the people of the United States to mark the observances with appropriate ceremonies and activities.